components. That's my favorite tool. I think I saw a LinkedIn post that you had about that as

00:48:12.719 --> 00:48:16.159
well. Like you don't have to just use a deep learning model just because.

00:48:19.360 --> 00:48:25.600
So, you know, usually like when I'm talking in a meetups on production, which I did,

00:48:26.639 --> 00:48:33.040
I had two of those in the last two weeks. I would say that, you know, if someone

00:48:33.600 --> 00:48:39.840
comes to me and say like, I can create a fancy deep learning models or some machine learning

00:48:39.840 --> 00:48:44.879
models, that's great. But if someone will come to me, I can deploy my linear regression in

00:48:44.879 --> 00:48:52.560
production. So this is a God. So I think that, you know, in the data science world today, at least

00:48:55.760 --> 00:49:03.520
it's more important that you can be able to take your work into production than

00:49:03.919 --> 00:49:11.840
don't do fancy stuff. Like if I can see my projection, my progress as a data science,

00:49:11.840 --> 00:49:17.679
like I feel like that I had a normal curve, like as any other data science in the room here, that

00:49:17.679 --> 00:49:25.120
when I was just starting as a really junior, I was into this deep learning machine and I was

00:49:25.919 --> 00:49:38.959
curious about it. And over time, I realized that if I need to run a model like for one hour,

00:49:38.959 --> 00:49:43.840
two hours to optimize it and probably get the same results as I would run linear regression,

00:49:45.280 --> 00:49:48.719
it's probably not worth it just for the sake of saying that I did

00:49:49.520 --> 00:49:56.719
something fancy. And if I cannot communicate it to others, like, you know, deploy it in a dashboard

00:49:56.719 --> 00:50:04.639
or deploy it somewhere, it's worthless because, you know, you're not getting the recognition. So

00:50:05.840 --> 00:50:10.639
today I think being like a full stack data scientist that you can

00:50:11.439 --> 00:50:14.159
take your work into production and it's super important.

00:50:14.159 --> 00:50:23.199
Thank you, Rami. I see Rob H., you've asked a question in the chat as well. Would you want

00:50:23.199 --> 00:50:31.439
to ask that one live? Sure. Yeah, just talking to lots of data scientists and organizations,

00:50:31.439 --> 00:50:37.919
it seems that often, not always, but often the highest value problems tend to be really complex

00:50:38.879 --> 00:50:43.919
and then sort of the dichotomy of the simpler problems, but they tend to be lower value.

00:50:44.479 --> 00:50:46.399
So I'm just curious how you navigate that.

00:50:48.639 --> 00:50:53.280
How do you make those priorities to make sure that you tackle, because you touched on it before,

00:50:53.280 --> 00:50:56.560
that's what made me think of it, you talked about the high, sort of the big problems.

00:50:58.639 --> 00:51:02.239
How do you make sure that the organization is actually tackling those?

00:51:03.199 --> 00:51:14.399
That's a good question. I would say that, you know, my approach is always to

00:51:15.439 --> 00:51:19.600
approach stuff with the most simple and approachable solution.

00:51:23.520 --> 00:51:30.560
And, you know, I always actually looking at the hanging fruit. Like if I see that the business,

00:51:31.520 --> 00:51:38.560
all the problems that there are, and usually there are more problems that we can actually

00:51:38.560 --> 00:51:45.600
solve because we're always bounded by resources. I always love to go first with the hanging fruits

00:51:45.600 --> 00:51:52.800
and start with those ones, because this is where I get my quick wins and then move to the complex.

00:51:53.439 --> 00:52:00.159
It's better to have something than nothing. It's another common phrase that our team is using.

00:52:02.159 --> 00:52:13.040
And iteration. So you don't need to solve the problem completely, you know, to spend one year

00:52:13.600 --> 00:52:16.959
just to solve a problem. If it's a complex stuff with something simple, you know,

00:52:17.760 --> 00:52:23.919
deliver after one or two and keep iterating, improve it. At least you deliver something,

00:52:23.919 --> 00:52:31.280
and, you know, the business start to see some value, rather than just do a long research and

00:52:31.280 --> 00:52:40.080
maybe get something after a year. I think that there is a trade-off, right? As long as you can

00:52:40.080 --> 00:52:44.479
articulate that it's not perfect and you need more time, but you're going to iterate and it's

00:52:44.479 --> 00:52:51.120
a process and the business understand, I think that's what I like to do. There are some cases,

00:52:51.120 --> 00:52:57.600
right, if you are, and it's not my domain, but if you are delivering a product for end users,

00:52:57.600 --> 00:53:04.080
so then this is where you definitely need to address the complexity and make sure that you

00:53:04.080 --> 00:53:08.879
solve it before you release it. But that's a different domain and I'm not in that domain.

00:53:09.679 --> 00:53:12.639
I hope this is answering your question.

00:53:14.479 --> 00:53:15.199
Yeah, thank you.

00:53:18.879 --> 00:53:25.120
Rami, a question from earlier was, have you had to teach R skills to members of your team?

00:53:25.760 --> 00:53:27.600
Do you have any tips for doing that?

00:53:28.719 --> 00:53:35.040
So, typically they teach me new stuff. I'm fortunate that I am surrounding with very

00:53:35.040 --> 00:53:42.800
smart people that they are, you know, we have lunch and learns. Actually, at 10 o'clock,

00:53:42.800 --> 00:53:49.760
I'm jumping to internal R meetup that we have. So, we're trying to do as many as

00:53:51.040 --> 00:53:58.959
those internal lunch and learn. If someone came and say, oh, I learn, I solve out to, you know,

00:53:58.959 --> 00:54:06.320
I learn how to create a pipeline with that tool or I learn how to build this with that tool or

00:54:06.320 --> 00:54:12.879
something like this. So, it's like the immediate response in our Slack is lunch and learn.

00:54:14.719 --> 00:54:20.399
And so, we're trying to create an environment that we share the knowledge

00:54:21.520 --> 00:54:25.760
and documentation is very important. If you learn something, we have like a big

00:54:25.760 --> 00:54:30.879
book down that we, any new tools that we're using, we are just documented,

00:54:30.879 --> 00:54:36.000
trying at least to document, not always doing a good job. At least I'm probably the worst in

00:54:37.919 --> 00:54:45.439
documented, but that's the culture that we're trying to create to make sure that we are sharing.

00:54:45.919 --> 00:54:53.679
That's awesome that you all do that. And I know one of the questions on a prior

00:54:55.280 --> 00:55:00.479
hangout was around like getting people to talk as well. And like, how do you find people to

00:55:00.479 --> 00:55:06.159
speak at these? And I love that you just say, you answer on Slack lunch and learn topic.

00:55:07.360 --> 00:55:09.760
Seems like a great way of getting topics, too.

00:55:10.239 --> 00:55:15.520
There's a general question that came in anonymously as well, which can be open to

00:55:15.520 --> 00:55:23.520
anybody. But do you think as an R-first analyst or data scientist, you could manage a team of non-R

00:55:23.520 --> 00:55:36.399
users? It should be as long as you're open and, you know, like, let's say that if tomorrow I need

00:55:36.479 --> 00:55:46.080
to manage a team that are Python users, probably I should learn some Python. Because I think it's,

00:55:46.080 --> 00:55:52.959
you know, as long as a manager, as I mentioned before, you are doing this coding, but like I

00:55:52.959 --> 00:56:00.800
do review code. I do, I want to, you know, when we have a code review, you still want to make sure

00:56:00.800 --> 00:56:08.879
that, you know, you understand what other folks are doing. So, I think in a, if you're still in

00:56:09.439 --> 00:56:18.320
that management level, you should probably be open to learn the other language, if it's a Python or

00:56:18.320 --> 00:56:23.760
any other language, to be involved and understand what the folks are doing.

00:56:24.639 --> 00:56:31.760
And I know you've already mentioned that team uses both R and Python. But someone asked, can

00:56:31.760 --> 00:56:36.080
you give a general example of when you would use R or when to use Python?

00:56:38.080 --> 00:56:44.399
So, most of the time I'm using R because, you know, from the data, when you're loading data,

00:56:44.399 --> 00:56:51.040
you're putting the data from APIs, the easy ways to, you know, put it with and process it with

00:56:51.120 --> 00:56:58.000
and process it with dplyr and all the other great tools. The case that I will use, for example,

00:56:58.000 --> 00:57:04.000
I'm using a lot of Bash, thanks to Denton, that is also here in this call.

00:57:06.800 --> 00:57:16.320
And when you try to automate R code in some command line environment, and this is where,

00:57:16.320 --> 00:57:25.360
you know, it's easier to do automation, call different R files, or if you're having some

00:57:25.360 --> 00:57:32.479
YAML file with a manifest of some job, instead of doing multiple steps, it's just, you know,

00:57:32.479 --> 00:57:39.919
we are calling it Bash script that doing those steps or in a Docker, when I'm building a Docker,

00:57:39.919 --> 00:57:47.919
I also like to use Bash to automate. So, that's an example. I had some example, like,

00:57:48.719 --> 00:57:57.679
if you need to pull some S3 objects. In the past, I used to, there is a Python package,

00:57:57.679 --> 00:58:05.919
library called Pluto3. So, it was kind of like the native library to pull S3 objects. So, I used this.

00:58:06.879 --> 00:58:08.879
But mostly, I'm using R.

